description:
"Inside the Machine: Art and Invention in the 20th Century" by Megan Prelinger at the 2016 Gray Area Festival.

Electronic engineers of the last century worked with generations of commercial artists to make their work visible, exposing processes that were otherwise enclosed in device cabinets and defining new technologies in persuasive visual terms. The applications of electronic wave forms in music, media, communications, and computing inspired artists to draw on a century’s worth of modernist and conceptual traditions in graphic art. The animation of typographic art as a tool to communicate technological specifics and program developments in the computing fields of the 1950s is detailed as a particular example of an artistic tradition extended beyond its original context when combined with a technological purpose.

The Gray Area Festival is four days of conference, performances, workshops, and exhibitions to discuss the impact of art and technology on culture. More at http://grayareafestival.io
